  &lt;p&gt;Miran,&lt;br&gt;
I think your explanation is correct and conistent with REST. However, &lt;br&gt;
in my personal opinion (some may disagree) it is also important for &lt;br&gt;
RESTful application to store its state on the client rather than on &lt;br&gt;
the server. That provides lots of benefits in real world &lt;br&gt;
implementation.&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
Cheers,&lt;br&gt;
Hovhannes&lt;br&gt;
